Introduction to Neural Networks: Bank Churn prediction¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary:¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customer’s location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values

** 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) ** 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# functions to treat outliers by flooring and capping


def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """
    Treats outliers in a variable

    df: dataframe
    col: dataframe column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned the value of Lower_Whisker
    # all the values greater than Upper_Whisker will be assigned the value of Upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df


def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    """
    Treat outliers in a list of variables

    df: dataframe
    col_list: list of dataframe columns
    """
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df, c)

    return df

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

It's important to consider the potential consequences of making wrong predictions. Two common prediction errors are:

False Positive: Predicting that a customer is exiting (Class 1) when they are not actually exiting (Class 0).

False Negative: Predicting that a customer is not exiting (Class 0) when they are actually exiting (Class 1).

Among these two errors, the more important one for the bank to minimize is the False Negative. Here's why:

Importance of Minimizing False Negatives:

Predicting that a customer is not exiting when they are actually leaving the bank can have significant financial consequences. In such cases, the bank may miss the opportunity to take proactive measures to retain those customers. These customers might be sensitive or dissatisfied for various reasons, and if their issues are not addressed promptly, they could leave, resulting in revenue loss for the bank.

Reducing False Negatives (Increasing Recall):

To reduce the risk of false negatives and increase Recall, which is the proportion of actual positives (churn cases) correctly predicted by the model, the bank can consider the following strategies:

Threshold Adjustment: By adjusting the classification threshold for the churn prediction model, you can increase sensitivity (recall) at the cost of specificity (precision). Lowering the threshold will classify more cases as positive (Class 1), which can help capture more true positives.

Feature Engineering: Carefully select and engineer features that are strong indicators of potential churn. Feature selection and extraction techniques can help improve the model's ability to identify at-risk customers.

Data Augmentation: Augment the dataset with additional data if possible. More data can help the model better capture the complexities of customer behavior and churn patterns.

Balancing the Dataset: If the dataset is imbalanced (i.e., there are far more non-churn cases than churn cases), consider techniques like oversampling the minority class (churn) or using synthetic data generation methods to balance the classes.

In summary, while both false positives and false negatives have their implications, in the context of customer churn prediction for a bank, minimizing false negatives (increasing Recall) is typically more critical. This ensures that the bank can proactively retain customers who are actually at risk of leaving, ultimately reducing revenue loss and maintaining customer loyalty.

def make_confusion_matrix(cf,
                          group_names=None,
                          categories='auto',
                          count=True,
                          percent=True,
                          cbar=True,
                          xyticks=True,
                          xyplotlabels=True,
                          sum_stats=True,
                          figsize=None,
                          cmap='Blues',
                          title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''

    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names) == cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(
            value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(
        group_labels, group_counts, group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0], cf.shape[1])

    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        # Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

        # if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
        if len(cf) == 2:
            # Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
            precision = cf[1, 1] / sum(cf[:, 1])
            recall = cf[1, 1] / sum(cf[1, :])
            f1_score = 2*precision*recall / (precision + recall)
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(
                accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score)
        else:
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
    else:
        stats_text = ""

    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize == None:
        # Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks == False:
        # Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories = False

    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf, annot=box_labels, fmt="", cmap=cmap, cbar=cbar,
                xticklabels=categories, yticklabels=categories)

    if xyplotlabels:
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label' + stats_text)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(stats_text)

    if title:
        plt.title(title)

def graphs_and_report(history, predicted):
    # Plot training & validation loss values
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('Model loss')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

    # Plot training & validation accuracy values
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Model accuracy')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

# Initializing the neural network model using the Sequential API
model1 = Sequential()

# Adding the input layer with 11 neurons and ReLU activation function
model1.add(Dense(11, activation='relu',
                 kernel_initializer='he_uniform', input_shape=(11,)))

# Adding the first hidden layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation function
model1.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))

# Adding the second hidden layer with 32 neurons and ReLU activation function
model1.add(Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))

# Adding the output layer with one neuron and sigmoid activation function
model1.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

# Setting Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) as the optimizer with a learning rate of 1e-3
sgd = optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=1e-3)

# Compiling the model with binary cross-entropy loss and accuracy as the evaluation metric
model1.compile(optimizer=sgd, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Printing a summary of the model architecture
model1.summary()

Observations¶

Precision (0): 0.839

  • Precision measures the accuracy of positive predictions for class 0. In this case, it indicates that when the model predicts class 0, it's usually correct.

Recall (0): 0.959

  • Recall (or Sensitivity) measures the ability of the model to correctly identify actual class 0 instances. It tells us what proportion of actual class 0 cases were correctly predicted.

F1-Score (0): 0.895

  • The F1-Score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall for class 0. It provides a balance between precision and recall for this class.

Precision (1): 0.645

  • Precision for class 1. Indicates how accurate the model's positive predictions are for class 1.

Recall (1): 0.286

  • Recall for class 1. Measures the ability to correctly identify actual class 1 instances.

F1-Score (1): 0.396

  • F1-Score for class 1. Similar to class 0, it balances precision and recall for class 1.

def best_threshold(model):
    # predict probabilities
    yhat = model.predict(X_train)
    # keep probabilities for the positive outcome only
    yhat = yhat[:, 0]
    # calculate roc curves
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, yhat)
    # calculate the g-mean for each threshold
    gmeans = np.sqrt(tpr * (1-fpr))
    # locate the index of the largest g-mean
    ix = np.argmax(gmeans)
    print('Best Threshold=%f, G-Mean=%.3f' % (thresholds[ix], gmeans[ix]))
    # plot the roc curve for the model
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, marker='.', label='Logistic')
    plt.scatter(fpr[ix], tpr[ix], marker='o', color='black', label='Best')
    # axis labels
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.legend()
    return thresholds[ix]
    # show the plot
    plt.show()

Observations¶

Precision (0): 0.924

  • Precision measures the accuracy of positive predictions for class 0. In this case, it indicates that when the model predicts class 0, it's usually correct.

Recall (0): 0.705

  • Recall (or Sensitivity) measures the ability of the model to correctly identify actual class 0 instances. It tells us what proportion of actual class 0 cases were correctly predicted.

F1-Score (0): 0.799

  • The F1-Score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall for class 0. It provides a balance between precision and recall for this class.

Precision (1): 0.403

  • Precision for class 1. Indicates how accurate the model's positive predictions are for class 1.

Recall (1): 0.774

  • Recall for class 1. Measures the ability to correctly identify actual class 1 instances.

F1-Score (1): 0.530

  • F1-Score for class 1. Similar to class 0, it balances precision and recall for class 1.

In [ ]:
# Initializing the neural network model using the Sequential API
model3 = Sequential()

# Adding the input layer with 64 neurons and ReLU activation function
model3.add(Dense(64, activation='relu',
                 kernel_initializer='he_uniform', input_shape=(11,)))

# Adding the second hidden layer with 32 neurons and ReLU activation function
model3.add(Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))

# Adding the output layer with one neuron and sigmoid activation function
model3.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

# Initializing the Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 1e-3
adam = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-3)

# Compiling the model with binary cross-entropy loss and accuracy as the evaluation metric
model3.compile(optimizer=adam, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Printing a summary of the model architecture
model3.summary()

Classification Report:¶

Precision (0): 0.911

  • Precision measures the accuracy of positive predictions for class 0. In this case, it indicates that when the model predicts class 0, it's usually correct.

Recall (0): 0.821

  • Recall (or Sensitivity) measures the ability of the model to correctly identify actual class 0 instances. It tells us what proportion of actual class 0 cases were correctly predicted.

F1-Score (0): 0.863

  • The F1-Score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall for class 0. It provides a balance between precision and recall for this class.

Precision (1): 0.497

  • Precision for class 1. Indicates how accurate the model's positive predictions are for class 1.

Recall (1): 0.687

  • Recall for class 1. Measures the ability to correctly identify actual class 1 instances.

F1-Score (1): 0.577

  • F1-Score for class 1. Similar to class 0, it balances precision and recall for class 1.

Model Improvement: Neural Network model with Dropout¶

Model 4¶

In [ ]:
import random
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(42)
random.seed(42)
tf.random.set_seed(42)
In [ ]:
# Initializing the neural network model 'model4'
model4 = Sequential()

# Adding the input layer with 64 neurons and ReLU as the activation function
model4.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform', input_shape=(11,)))

# Adding a dropout layer with a dropout rate of 20% to prevent overfitting
model4.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Adding the second hidden layer with 32 neurons and ReLU as the activation function
model4.add(Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))

# Adding another dropout layer with a dropout rate of 20%
model4.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Adding the output layer with one neuron and sigmoid as the activation function
model4.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

# Defining the stochastic gradient descent (SGD) optimizer with a learning rate of 1e-3
sgd = optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=1e-3)

# Compiling the model using binary cross-entropy loss and accuracy as a metric
model4.compile(optimizer=sgd, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Printing a summary of the model architecture
model4.summary()

# Define early stopping criteria to prevent overfitting
early_stop = callbacks.EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_loss', min_delta=0.001, patience=5)

def create_model(dropout_rate=0.0, lr=0.001, layer_1=64, layer_2=32):
    """
    Create a neural network model with customizable dropout rates, learning rate, and layer sizes.

    Parameters:
    - dropout_rate: The dropout rate applied to hidden layers.
    - lr: The learning rate for the optimizer.
    - layer_1: Number of neurons in the first hidden layer.
    - layer_2: Number of neurons in the second hidden layer.

    Returns:
    A compiled Keras model.
    """

    # Initializing the neural network model
    model = Sequential()

    # Adding the input layer with ReLU activation and He uniform initialization
    model.add(Dense(layer_1, kernel_initializer='he_uniform', activation='relu', input_dim=X_train.shape[1]))

    # Adding dropout to the input layer with a customizable dropout rate
    model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))

    # Adding the hidden layer with ReLU activation and He uniform initialization
    model.add(Dense(layer_2, kernel_initializer='he_uniform', activation='relu'))

    # Adding dropout to the hidden layer with a customizable dropout rate
    model.add(Dropout(dropout_rate))

    # Adding the output layer with sigmoid activation for binary classification
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    # Initializing the optimizer (Stochastic Gradient Descent with the specified learning rate)
    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=lr)

    # Compiling the model with binary cross-entropy as the loss and accuracy as a metric
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

# Creating a KerasClassifier based on the custom create_model function

    "batch_size": [32, 64, 128],
    "lr": [0.01, 0.001, 0.1],
    "dropout_rate": [0.0, 0.2, 0.5]
}

# Number of splits for k-fold cross-validation

# Initializing the GridSearchCV with the Keras estimator, hyperparameter grid, and cross-validation settings
grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=keras_estimator, verbose=1, cv=kfold_splits, param_grid=param_grid, n_jobs=-1)

# Performing grid search with cross-validation on the training data and validation data

Observations¶

Precision (0): 0.915

  • Precision measures the accuracy of positive predictions for class 0. In this case, it indicates that when the model predicts class 0, it's usually correct.

Recall (0): 0.768

  • Recall (or Sensitivity) measures the ability of the model to correctly identify actual class 0 instances. It tells us what proportion of actual class 0 cases were correctly predicted.

F1-Score (0): 0.835

  • The F1-Score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall for class 0. It provides a balance between precision and recall for this class.

Precision (1): 0.445

  • Precision for class 1. Indicates how accurate the model's positive predictions are for class 1.

Recall (1): 0.722

  • Recall for class 1. Measures the ability to correctly identify actual class 1 instances.

F1-Score (1): 0.550

  • F1-Score for class 1. Similar to class 0, it balances precision and recall for class 1.

Observations¶

Evaluating the models:

Model 1: It has a high precision for class 0 but a low recall for class 1, which suggests it may not be the best choice if you want to correctly identify class 1 instances.

Model 2: It has a higher recall for class 1 compared to Model 1, but its precision for class 1 is quite low. It also has a lower overall accuracy than Model 1.

Model 3: This model has a good balance between precision and recall for both classes, making it a reasonable choice. It also has a decent overall accuracy.

Model 4: While it has a high recall for class 1, its precision is low. The overall accuracy is also lower compared to other models.

Model 5: Model 5 shows a decent balance between precision and recall for both classes, along with a good overall accuracy.

Model 6: Model 6 has a higher recall for class 1, but its precision for class 1 is lower. The overall accuracy is also lower compared to some other models.

Conclusion¶

Based on the metrics and the priority of maximizing recall for class 1 (identifying positive cases), Model 5 might be a preferable choice. It has a higher recall for class 1 (0.687) compared to Model 3, which could be crucial if the goal is to minimize false negatives, even though it has slightly lower precision (0.497).

Model 5 offers a good balance between recall and overall accuracy.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

What recommedations would you suggest to the bank?

Customer Segmentation:

  • Segment customers based on age groups, account balances, and credit scores. Tailor marketing and service strategies for each segment. For example, offer retirement planning services for older customers and financial education for those with lower balances or credit scores.

Retention Programs:

  • Develop customer retention programs that incentivize and reward active members. These programs could include loyalty rewards, discounts, or special offers for long-standing customers who actively use the bank's services.

Cross-Selling:

  • Implement targeted cross-selling strategies to increase the number of products per customer. Identify complementary financial products and services to offer based on individual customer profiles. Ensure that the cross-selling approach is customer-centric and adds value.

Customer Feedback:

  • Collect regular feedback from customers to understand their needs, concerns, and reasons for potential churn. Use surveys, focus groups, and digital feedback channels to gather insights.

Enhanced Customer Experience:

  • Continuously improve the overall customer experience. Ensure that online and mobile banking platforms are user-friendly and provide seamless services. Address any issues related to account management, transactions, or customer support promptly.
